{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476525"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13775"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13775"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.09,0.39,0.01,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6394"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53991"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6394"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39462"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"3049"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12501"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44177"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53991"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old girl is brought to the Emergency Department by her parents with acute onset of confusion and agitation. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears agitated and her skin is flushed and dry. Her pupils are dilated bilaterally. She has a pulse rate of 160/min (normal range 70-110), blood pressure 100/60 mmHg (50th percentile 94/56), respiratory rate 30/min (normal range 20-30), SpO2 98% on room air and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications, if ingested, would best explain this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paracetamol","Aspirin","Diphenhydramine","Amoxicillin","Methylphenidate"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child\u0027s presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ediphenhydramine\u003C/strong\u003E overdose causing an anticholinergic toxidrome. Diphenhydramine is a first-generation H1 antihistamine with significant anticholinergic properties. The anticholinergic toxidrome is classically characterised by \u0022mad as a hatter\u0022 (altered mental status, agitation, hallucinations), \u0022red as a beet\u0022 (flushing), \u0022dry as a bone\u0022 (dry skin and mucous membranes), \u0022blind as a bat\u0022 (mydriasis), and \u0022hot as a hare\u0022 (hyperthermia). This patient demonstrates all of these features. Additional signs include tachycardia and urinary retention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E overdose does not typically cause acute confusion or anticholinergic signs. In large ingestions, it can lead to hepatotoxicity over the course of days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E (salicylate) toxicity can present with altered mental status, tachypnoea, tachycardia, and hyperthermia. However, it characteristically causes diaphoresis and respiratory alkalosis, rather than the dry skin seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is a commonly prescribed antibiotic in children. Overdose may cause nausea, vomiting, and diarrhoea, but would not explain the anticholinergic signs in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethylphenidate\u003C/strong\u003E is a stimulant medication used for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. As a sympathomimetic, overdose can cause agitation, tachycardia, hypertension, and hyperthermia. However, it would also be expected to cause diaphoresis and less pronounced mydriasis compared to the anticholinergic toxidrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anticholinergic toxidrome is characterised by mydriasis, dry skin, hyperthermia, tachycardia, urinary retention, and altered mental status.","Diphenhydramine is a first-generation H1 antihistamine with significant anticholinergic effects.","Supportive care is the mainstay of treatment for diphenhydramine overdose."],"references":["Anticholinergic Syndrome. In: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital clinical practice guidelines [online]. 2017 [Accessed 2024 Jun 24]. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Anticholinergic_Syndrome/","Patel J, Edwards J. Treating Diphenhydramine Overdose: A Literature Review of Currently Available Treatment Methods. Toxics. 2024;12(6):376. Available at: https://doi.org/10.3390/toxics12060376"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39462"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13775"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39462"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-28T15:14:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-28T15:22:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6394"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53991"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"